#compdef mhtml-to-html
# ============================================================================
# mhtml-to-html - convert MHTML archives to single-file HTML
#                  (JavaScript, MIT)
#
# Author : Gildas Lormeau (gildas-lormeau)
# Upstream: https://github.com/gildas-lormeau/mhtml-to-html
# npm    : mhtml-to-html (binary: mhtml-to-html)
# Also published as Deno via JSR + an Erwan LC web app
#
# `mhtml-to-html` is a JavaScript library + CLI for
# unpacking MHTML (.mht / .mhtml) archive files into
# self-contained single-file HTML pages. MHTML is the
# multipart-MIME-encoded "Web Page, Complete" save
# format used by IE 5+, Edge, Chrome, Opera, and the
# Wayback Machine ARC-then-WARC pipeline for archiving
# fully-rendered web pages with inline images, CSS,
# fonts, and script resources. The output is a single
# HTML file with all resources re-inlined as data:
# URIs - viewable in any browser without needing the
# original MHTML container format.
#
# Usage:
#   mhtml-to-html <input>... [--output <output>]
#                            [--enable-scripts]
#                            [--fetch-missing-resources]
#                            [--help] [--version]
#
# Flags:
#   --output <output>             output HTML file
#                                 (default: input file
#                                 with .html extension;
#                                 only used when a single
#                                 input is provided)
#   --enable-scripts              re-enable embedded
#                                 <script> tags in the
#                                 output (default: scripts
#                                 are stripped for safety)
#   --fetch-missing-resources     for resources referenced
#                                 by the MHTML but absent
#                                 from the archive, fetch
#                                 them from the original
#                                 URL at conversion time
#   --help                        print help message
#   --version                     print version number
#
# Input arguments support glob patterns (`*.mht`,
# `*.mhtml`) - the CLI expands globs via the npm `glob`
# package + iterates each match.
#
# The parse5 lane is built on `parse5 ^8.0.0` (declared
# verbatim at upstream package.json HEAD as a direct
# dep, imported from lib/dom-parser-node.js), the
# canonical Node HTML5 parser by Ivan Nikulin (inikulin)
# - github.com/inikulin/parse5, 3700+ stars. parse5 is
# a pure-JS WHATWG-spec-compliant HTML5 parser + serializer
# with bidirectional reversible parsing (the parse-then-
# serialize round trip preserves original byte sequences
# byte-for-byte where the spec allows). The library is
# the de-facto Node HTML5 parser and is bundled / re-
# exported by:
#   - cheerio (the "jQuery for the server" library)
#   - jsdom (DOM emulation for headless test envs)
#   - Angular SSR (server-side render)
#   - React Server Components implementations
#   - rehype (markdown+HTML AST processing)
#
# mhtml-to-html uses parse5 in `lib/dom-parser-node.js`:
# `parse(mhtmlPartHtml)` constructs the full DOM,
# `defaultTreeAdapter` provides node manipulation
# primitives, and the `html` namespace constants are
# used to identify void / raw-text tag categories. The
# DOM is then walked + `<img>` / `<link>` / `<script>`
# / `<source>` references are re-inlined as data: URIs
# from the corresponding MHTML multipart sections,
# producing the single-file HTML output.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 242 :: HTML5 parsing (WHATWG-spec-compliant DOM
#              construction + CSS selectors)
# Round 1426 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 242
#                                       (235th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : servo/html5ever (+ scraper) [R1424 _docrawl]
#   Go      : golang.org/x/net/html       [R1425 _html-tool]
#   TS/Node : inikulin/parse5             [R1426 THIS FILE]
#
# parse5 closes Axis 242 with the *single-author root-
# of-trust* pattern. Ivan Nikulin has maintained parse5
# since 2013, and it has been the unmoved canonical
# Node HTML5 parser for the entire intervening decade.
# The three lanes form a clean spectrum of "where did
# the canonical HTML5 parser come from in this ecosystem":
#
#   - Rust (servo/html5ever): extracted from Mozilla's
#     Servo browser engine - a real browser engine
#     spinoff
#   - Go (golang.org/x/net/html): Go core team
#     implementation in the golang.org/x/net subrepo -
#     core-team-maintained-adjacent-to-stdlib
#   - Node (inikulin/parse5): independent third-party
#     project that became the de-facto root-of-trust
#     for the whole Node HTML5 ecosystem - cheerio,
#     jsdom, Angular SSR all depend on it
#
# parse5's pure-JS implementation matters for the Node
# ecosystem because:
#   - no native bindings required - works in Node + Deno
#     + Bun + browser bundles + Cloudflare Workers
#   - byte-for-byte WHATWG spec conformance via the
#     html5lib test suite
#   - reversible parse-then-serialize preserves the
#     original byte sequences where the spec doesn't
#     require normalization (lets HTML rewriting tools
#     emit minimal diffs)
#
# Cross-language interop happens at the DOM-structure
# level: the same input HTML parsed by html5ever vs
# x/net/html vs parse5 produces structurally identical
# trees (modulo per-library node-type extensions). The
# in-memory representation differs:
#   - html5ever via scraper: `ego_tree::Tree<Node>` with
#     arena-allocated nodes
#   - golang.org/x/net/html: `*html.Node` doubly-linked
#     tree
#   - parse5: JS object tree with parentNode / childNodes
#     / attrs fields
# Inter-lane portability requires re-serialization to
# HTML (or to JSON-LD / Markdown pivots).
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - docrawl (Rust, scraper + html5ever): same-origin
#     documentation-site crawler with HTML -> Markdown
#     conversion
#   - html-tool (Go, golang.org/x/net/html): pipe-friendly
#     extractor for tags / attribs / comments / CSS-
#     queries from URLs/files on stdin
#   - mhtml-to-html (Node, parse5): MHTML archive
#     unpacker producing single-file HTML output with
#     resources re-inlined as data: URIs
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (web-corpus
# extraction / pipe-friendly text extraction / archive
# format conversion), all converging on the WHATWG HTML
# Living Standard.
#
# Axis 242 closes the round 1426 cycle - 235th axis closed
# total.
# ============================================================================

_mhtml-to-html() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--output[output HTML file (single-input only)]:file:_files -g "*.{html,htm}"' \
        '--enable-scripts[re-enable embedded <script> tags (default off)]' \
        '--fetch-missing-resources[fetch absent resources from their original URLs]' \
        '(- *)--help[print help message]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version number]' \
        '*:input MHTML file(s):_files -g "*.{mht,mhtml}"'
}

_mhtml-to-html "$@"
